From Effectiveness to Efficiency: Comparative
Evaluation of Code Generated by LCGMs for
Bilingual Programming Questions
Weipeng Jiang∗, Xuanqi Gao∗, Juan Zhai†, Shiqing Ma†, Xiaoyu Zhang∗, Chao Shen∗‡
∗School of Cyber Science and Engineering
Xi’an Jiaotong University
lenijwp, gxq2000, zxy0927@stu.xjtu.edu.cn, chaoshen@xjtu.edu.cn
†Manning College of Information & Computer Sciences
University of Massachusetts, Amherst
juanzhai, shiqingma@umass.edu
Abstract—Large Code Generation Models (LCGMs) have
garnered significant attention and achieved promising results
across various programming tasks. However, concerns arise
regarding performance when using non-English prompts, as these
models are primarily trained on English-centric corpora, and
most programming language tokens resemble English. Existing
benchmarks often rely on English programming questions and
limited manual unit test cases, inadequately assessing LCGMgenerated code quality. This paper investigates code quality differences, specifically effectiveness and efficiency, when employing
different natural languages as inputs, focusing on Chinese and
English due to their prominent corpora and LCGM availability.
Evaluating LCGM-generated code quality under bilingual inputs
presents three challenges: (1) lack of high-quality bilingual
programming question datasets, (2) insufficient unit test cases for
comprehensive correctness verification, and (3) limited support
for comparing generated code performance. To address these
challenges, we curated a test suite of 52 bilingual programming
questions and developed automated input generators for each.
We enhanced correctness verification by sampling larger unit test
cases and estimated code performance by profiling execution time
relative to input size growth. Using this framework, we conducted
an empirical study on six state-of-the-art LCGMs. The results
revealed that LCGM-generated code exhibits varying bilingual
correctness on an average of 10.5% of tasks, with 39.5% of
correct code showing diverse bilingual performance differences.
Our findings suggested LCGMs may not consistently generate
high-quality code across different languages, providing insights
for future research directions.
Index Terms—Large Code Generation Models, Code Quality,
Effectiveness and Efficiency, Bilingual Evaluation
I. INTRODUCTION
The rapid advancement of Large Code Generation Models (LCGMs) has revolutionized the field of software engineering, offering promising solutions to a wide range of
programming tasks. These models, built on the architecture
of large language models and trained on vast corpora of
source code, have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in
generating functional code snippets [1], [2], assisting with
1‡: Chao Shen is the corresponding author. Email: chaoshen@xjtu.edu.cn
programming tasks [3], [4], [5], and even automating entire
software development workflows [6], [7].
While LCGMs support multiple input languages, facilitating
developers to describe requirements in their preferred natural
language, a critical question arises concerning the consistency
of code generation capabilities across languages. This concern
is particularly significant as LCGMs are predominantly trained
on English-centric corpora, potentially impacting their performance when prompted with inputs in other languages. Furthermore, the fact that most programming languages originate
from English, e.g., using English words as reserved keywords,
further exacerbates this concern.
Existing evaluation benchmarks for LCGMs primarily focus
on English programming questions and rely on a limited
number of manually crafted unit test cases for code correctness
validation [8], [9], lacking a comprehensive assessment of
code quality, especially regarding generation effectiveness
and efficiency. The absence of diverse input languages in
these benchmarks hinders understanding the performance of
LCGMs when prompted with various natural languages. Moreover, measuring the efficiency of the generated code itself is
a challenging problem.
This paper aims to address this research gap by conducting
the first extensive empirical study to comprehensively observe
and compare the code quality differences of mainstream
LCGMs on multilingual programming questions. Specifically,
we focus on English and Chinese, as these languages have
a significant presence in the programming community and a
wealth of available LCGMs and corpora [10]. By conducting
a comparative analysis of the LCGM-generated code for
bilingual programming questions, we aim to shed light on
the potential disparities in code quality and provide insights
into the factors influencing these differences. We design the
following three research questions to assess the differences in
LCGM-generated code across English and Chinese:
• (RQ1) Are LCGM-generated code equally effective
when using bilingual programming questions?
arXiv:2406.00602v1 [cs.SE] 2 Jun 2024 • (RQ2) Are LCGM-generated code equally efficient
when using bilingual programming questions?
• (RQ3) What is the impact of prompting on bilingual
quality differences across languages?
Evaluating the quality of LCGM-generated code under
bilingual inputs poses several challenges. Firstly, there is a
scarcity of high-quality bilingual parallel programming questions datasets that can serve as a reliable benchmark. Secondly,
the limited number of unit test cases used in existing benchmarks may not adequately ensure the thorough correctness
verification of the generated code [11]. Lastly, there is a lack of
support for measuring and comparing the performance of the
generated code, which is crucial for assessing their efficiency.
To address these challenges, we have carefully curated a
comprehensive test suite of 52 bilingual programming questions through a rigorous manual preparation process. Furthermore, we develop automated input generators for each
programming question, which facilitate the generation of a
variety of test cases. We improve the correctness verification
process by extensively sampling larger unit test cases using our
input generator. To measure the performance of the generated
code, we implement a profiling mechanism that measures the
code execution time relative to the growth of the input size.
This allows us to compare the efficiency of the generated code
across different languages and input sizes.
Using this evaluation framework, we conduct an empirical
study on six state-of-the-art LCGMs. According to our results,
we summarize a series of findings and implications that may
guide future research on the consistency of LCGM multilingual capabilities. We highlight some key findings as follows:
1) Existing LCGMs exhibit significant disparities in both
effectiveness and efficiency when generating code for
programming questions separately presented in English
and Chinese.
2) As the temperature parameter increases, the quality of
code generated by most LCGMs tends to shift from
favoring Chinese towards favoring English.
3) Different prompting strategies significantly impact the
bilingual code quality generated by LCGMs, highlighting the potential of prompting to alleviate the crosslinguistic performance gap, suggesting it as a potential
area for further research.
Overall, our work confirms that LCGMs do not consistently
generate high-quality code across different languages, highlighting the need for further investigation into the factors
influencing these disparities.
Contributions. The contributions of this paper are as follows:
• We conduct the first study specifically focusing on investigating the code quality differences of LCGMs on
English-Chinese bilingual programming questions.
• We collect a dataset of 52 bilingual programming questions and perform a systematic evaluation on six mainstream LCGMs, observing that the LCGM-generated
code shows different bilingual correctness on an average
of 10.5% programming tasks, where 39.5% correct code
also exhibits diverse bilingual performance differences.
• We summarize a series of findings and implications, then
provide guidance and inspiration for future research.
• We release our dataset and evaluation framework [12],
aiming to facilitate further research on multilingual code
generation quality assessment.
II. BACKGROUND
Large Language Models (LLMs) denote language models
characterized by billions of parameters, meticulously trained
on extensive textual corpora to excel in various language
processing assignments. Particularly, Large Code Generation
Models undergo training and fine-tuning procedures specifically designed for programming languages, thereby augmenting their proficiency in executing software engineering
tasks [13], [14]. The success of these models can be attributed
to their training on vast corpora of code and natural language
data, which allows them to learn the intricate patterns, syntax,
and semantics of programming languages.
Thus, the quality of the training corpus of LCGMs is
a critical factor in determining the accuracy, diversity, and
contextual relevance of the code they generate. The training
corpora used for these LCGMs typically consist of a diverse
collection of open-source code repositories, such as those
hosted on GitHub [15]. These repositories encompass a wide
range of programming languages, e.g., Python, Java, C++, and
JavaScript. However, it is important to recognize that these
repositories are English-heavy, i.e., project descriptions, functional documentations, code comments, and issue discussions
are always written in English, as it is the predominant language
used in global software development [10]. Additionally, many
programming languages, such as Python and Java, have syntax
and keywords that closely resemble English words and phrases
[16]. Consequently, the datasets used for training LCGMs
are heavily skewed towards English-language content. This
linguistic disparity raises concerns regarding the effectiveness
of LCGMs in supporting and generating code for tasks presented in languages other than English, particularly those with
distinct linguistic structures. Naturally, this leads to an urgent
need for an in-depth analysis of whether LCGMs exhibit
consistent capabilities and quality in generating code across
different languages. Unfortunately, existing code generation
evaluation benchmarks (e.g., HumanEval [8] and MBPP [9])
fail to address this question, as they predominantly focus on
English programming challenges. Besides, these benchmarks
focus on providing unit test cases to verify the correctness of
code generated by LCGMs. In software engineering practice,
assessing code quality often requires consideration of additional factors beyond correctness, such as code efficiency.
III. STUDY DESIGN
A. Goals and Research Questions
To investigate the performance disparities of LCGMs in
generating code across English and other languages, we select
Chinese as a comparative case study. Chinese is one of

the most widely spoken languages globally and also one of
the most popular languages among software developers and
targeted users of LCGMs. Owing to the rapid growth of the
Chinese software industry [17], the scale of Chinese corpora (e.g., GitHub repositories with Chinese documentation)
is substantial, relative to other non-English languages. As
such, most LCGMs show strong performance on leaderboards
related to Chinese programming tasks [18]. Moreover, Chinese exhibits significant linguistic divergence from English in
terms of its writing system, grammatical structure, and lexical
inventory [19], presenting a distinct challenge for LCGMs
predominantly trained on English-heavy corpora. Our study
aims to conduct a fine-grained comparative analysis of the
code generation quality (i.e., both effectiveness and efficiency)
of existing LCGMs when presented with programming tasks
in English and Chinese.
However, this investigation encounters several challenges.
Firstly, there is a shortage of high-quality bilingual parallel
programming question datasets. Existing datasets mainly provide questions in English. Secondly, current benchmarks for
evaluating code effectiveness often rely on a limited number of
unit test cases, which have been proven to be insufficient [11].
Furthermore, those benchmarks do not emphasize measuring
the efficiency of the generated code, resulting in a lack of readily available measurement tools. To address these challenges,
we propose a novel evaluation framework in this paper that
includes a carefully curated bilingual programming question
dataset. This framework enables us to validate the correctness
of the generated code and estimate its execution performance
under various inputs, thereby facilitating the assessment of
the effectiveness and efficiency of LCGMs in generating code
for bilingual programming questions and further exploring
the quality differences. Ultimately, based on the proposed
framework, we aim to answer the following research questions:
• RQ1: Are LCGM-generated code equally effective when
using bilingual programming questions?
• RQ2: Are LCGM-generated code equally efficient when
using bilingual programming questions?
• RQ3: What is the impact of prompting on bilingual
quality differences across languages?
B. Evaluation Framework
1) Design Overview: To enable simultaneous measurement
of the effectiveness and efficiency of LCGM-generated code
for bilingual programming questions, we propose a framework,
consisting of four steps: dataset collection, code generation,
correctness verification, and performance estimation. Figure 1
illustrates our framework. We begin by selecting appropriate
programming questions and canonical solutions from mainstream LCGMs benchmarks, and meticulously preparing bilingual (English-Chinese) versions. We also construct an input
generator to automatically create test inputs of various sizes for
each question ( 1 ). Next, we input the bilingual programming
questions into the LCGM, considering different prompting
methods ( 2 ). This allows us to investigate the impact of
prompting on the quality of generated code in both languages.
To assess the effectiveness(RQ1), we verify the correctness
of the generated code by comparing its output results with
the canonical solution using unit test cases from the input
generator ( 3 ). To evaluate the efficiency(RQ2), we collect
“input size-execution time” pairs for functionally correct code
by running them with different input sizes and fitting them to
common time complexity expressions to estimate the average
execution performance ( 4 ). Besides, this framework also
supports the investigation of the impact of prompting by
allowing customizing various prompts used by code generation
(RQ3). With the verified correctness and average execution
performance, we gain insights into the quality of LCGMgenerated code.
2) Dataset Collection: Existing benchmarks usually provide many meticulously crafted programming tasks for evaluating the correctness of LCGM-generated code, which typically include task descriptions, program entries, input/output
examples, canonical solutions, and a few unit test cases. We
use three popular datasets, HumanEval [8], MBPP [9], and
LeetCode [20] as the initial question list, where requiring
LCGMs to fill in Python code segments based on specific task
descriptions and program entry points. To keep the quality
and suitability of the test suite, we then filter programming
questions based on the following criteria: (i) ensuring that
the tasks are of moderate difficulty level to prevent LCGMs
from struggling to generate correct answers in both bilingual
inputs, (ii) ensuring that the tasks have multiple potential
solutions to increase the likelihood of observing performance
differences, and (iii) ensuring that the tasks take a variable
with varying dimensionality as inputs, e.g., an array or list,
where the execution time of the solutions is strongly correlated
with the dimensionality of the input variable. After careful
screening, we ultimately select 52 programming questions,
covering a diverse range of problem types, such as dynamic
3 programming, string processing, array enumeration, and more.
Although this dataset is only half the size of HumanEval, it is
sufficient to show the quality differences in LCGM-generated
code for bilingual inputs, as demonstrated in §IV.
The questions collected from HumanEval and MBPP are
initially in English. Two authors proficient in both languages
meticulously translate them into Chinese. For questions from
LeetCode, which provides official bilingual versions, we adopt
them directly. We thoroughly check all bilingual question pairs
to ensure their consistency in task descriptions and adherence
to the respective language conventions. Additionally, for each
programming question, we provide an automated input sample
generator, denoted as G. It takes an input size parameter ni
that determines the dimensionality of the generated variables.
These variables are tailored to act as unit test inputs for the
specific programming questions. By varying the size parameter, G can generate a wide range of inputs, from small and
simple cases to large and complicated ones.
Our test suite can be formally represented as D = ⟨Q, S, G⟩,
where Q is the programming question, S is the canonical
solution, and G is the test input generator. Q consists of a
task description, an entry point function name, and reference
input/output. For each question q ∈ Q, we have two bilingual
parallel versions, qen and qzh, presented in English and
Chinese, respectively. S is the canonical solution of the given
programming questions, which is used to produce ground truth
outputs for correctness verification. G is a crucial component,
serving as the input generator. By leveraging G, we can
automatically generate a diverse set of test cases, saving
time and effort compared to manually generating inputs while
maintaining high quality and coverage.
3) Code Generation: While LCGMs demonstrate impressive code generation capabilities, accurately extracting the
desired code from their responses remains an engineering
challenge. Typically, many LCGMs struggle to precisely terminate their generation process after completing the target
function, often continuing to generate extraneous code until
reaching the maximum token limit. Directly executing such
code in a sandbox environment, e.g., provided by HumanEval,
frequently triggers parsing errors or interference from the
additional functions. To minimize this interference, we perform an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) based analysis on the
generated results. By traversing the AST, we identify and
extract only the code segments corresponding to the target
function specified by the entry point. This targeted extraction
ensures that only the code essential to the function’s execution
is retained, thereby reducing the likelihood of errors that may
arise from the inclusion of non-essential or erroneous code
segments. This preprocessing is crucial in accurately assessing
the correctness of the LCGMs’ outputs and ensuring that the
evaluation is not compromised by the LCGMs’ tendency to
generate superfluous code.
4) Correctness Verification: As discussed earlier, only a
few test cases in existing benchmarks are often insufficient
to guarantee thorough functionality correctness judgement,
such a concern is also highlighted in recent studies [11]. To

ensure the adequacy of unit testing, we automatically generate
larger-size test cases for correctness verification. As aforementioned, our collected dataset includes an input generator,
which can generate random inputs of a specified size. With
the canonical solution S, we can automatically synthesize
reference outputs, i.e., ground truth. Therefore, we can conduct
more comprehensive unit testing. We draw inspiration from
HumanEval’s approach, which involves executing the code in a
sandbox environment and verifying correctness by comparing
the output of the LCGM-generated code with the synthesized
ground truth. By comparing the differences in functionality
correctness of LCGM-generated code across bilingual versions
of the same programming question, we can conduct further
statistical analysis to support the investigation of RQ1.
Furthermore, we filter out the functionally correct code
based on extensive unit testing. Prioritizing correctness verification lays a solid foundation for subsequent performance
estimation, as discussing the performance merits of code with
inherent functional errors lacks practical significance.
5) Performance Estimation: Accurately characterizing and
evaluating the execution performance or time complexity
of arbitrary code is often challenging, especially when the
LCGM-generated code may contain external function calls.
In our framework, we estimate the execution performance by
sampling a large number of inputs and observing the changes
in the execution time of the LCGM-generated code as the
input size grows. Recall that with the input generator G,
we can sample test inputs of various sizes for the undermeasuring code by generating input variables with different
dimensions, thereby enabling us to profile actual execution
time for LCGM-generate code across different input sizes.
Initially, when constructing the input generator, we empirically set an initial maximum input size Nmax for each
programming question, taking into account the complexity of
the canonical solution. This value is set to be sufficiently large,
allowing us to divide it into many segments to sample different
input sizes. However, a problem arises as the LCGM-generate
code could have a higher complexity than the canonical solution, leading to excessively long execution times and making
the overall evaluation time prohibitively expensive. To address
this problem, we design an adaptive mechanism for adjusting
the maximum input size. Following HumanEval, we first set a
maximum time limit Tmax for code execution. Subsequently,
we examine the execution of each LCGM-generated code to
determine if it triggers a timeout when processing inputs of
size Nmax. In the event of a timeout, we iteratively decrease
4 Nmax by half until the execution satisfies the Tmax constraint.
With the maximum input size Nmax, we divide it into seg
equal parts and obtain an increasing sequence of input sizes:

We present a summary of seven prevalent time complexity
types, as illustrated in Table I. To determine the most matching time complexity type and corresponding mathematical
expression, we employ the least squares method to perform
a regression analysis [21] on the time series data (NT).
This approach enables us to identify the closest matching
complexity type. Additionally, we assign a score ranging from
1 to 7 to each time complexity type, following the order
presented in Table I. Lower scores indicate higher efficiency in
terms of actual code execution. With this scoring mechanism,
we can quantitatively compare the efficiency of two code
pieces in actual sampling-based execution.
C. Measurement Metrics
In this study, we focus on measuring the bilingual quality
differences in LCGM-generated code.
1) Effectiveness: The effectiveness is measured through the
correctness verification procedure. The function CorV er takes
a problem q as input and returns a boolean value. It returns
T rue if the problem q has been correctly solved by the target
LCGM, and F alse otherwise. Thus, we define the following
evaluation metrics:
• CRen (Correctness Rate in English): This metric represents
the proportion of programming questions in English for which
the target LCGM can generate correct code. The specific
calculation can be formalized as:
CRen =
|q ∈ Q : CorVer(qen) = T rue|
|Q|
• CRzh (Correctness Rate in Chinese): Similarly, this metric
represents the proportion of programming questions in Chinese
for which the target LCGM can generate correct code. It is
calculated as:
CRzh =
|q ∈ Q : CorVer(qzh) = T rue|
|Q|
• CRbi (Correctness Rate in Bilingual): This metric represents the proportion of programming questions for which the
target LCGM can generate correct code in both languages. It
is calculated as:
CRbi =
|q ∈ Q : CorVer(qen) ∧ CorVer(qzh) = True|
|Q|
• CDR (Correctness Difference Rate): This metric represents
the proportion of programming questions for which the target
LCGM can generate correct code only for one specific language. It is calculated as:
CDR =
|q ∈ Q : CorVer(qen) ⊕ CorVer(qzh) = Ture|
|Q|
where ⊕ is the XOR operator.
2) Efficiency: As aforementioned, we evaluate the efficiency differences on the programming questions subset where
LCGMs can generate correct solutions for both bilingual
inputs. Firstly, we define the subset of correctly solved programming questions as Q′ ⊆ Q, which satisfies

Besides, we introduce SComplex as a function that inputs a
programming question q and returns the score of the estimated
complexity for the LCGM-generated code. The score is a value
from 1 to 7, with lower scores indicating higher efficiency in
terms of actual code execution. The measurement metrics for
efficiency are as follows:
• PARen (Performance Advantage Rate in English): This
metric represents the proportion of programming questions in
Q′for which the LCGMs generate code with better estimated
time complexity (lower SComplex value) in English compared to Chinese. It is calculated as:
PARen =
|q ∈ Q′: SComplex(qen) < SComplex(qzh)|
|Q′|
• PARzh (Performance Advantage Rate in Chinese): This
metric represents the proportion of programming questions in
Q′for which the LCGMs generate code with better estimated
time complexity (lower SComplex score) in Chinese compared to English. It is calculated as:
PARzh =
|q ∈ Q′: SComplex(qzh) < SComplex(qen)|
|Q′|
• PDR (Performance Difference Rate): This metric represents
the proportion of programming questions in Q′for which the
LCGMs generate code with significantly different estimated

PDR =

D. Target LCGMs
We select the following six LCGMs in our study, considering: 1) English and Chinese are well-supported; 2) they
top mainstream evaluation benchmarks and leaderboards (for
Python code generation); 3) they are representative and diverse
in architecture, i.e., originating from different model families;
and 4) due to our GPU constraints, the open-source models
do not exceed 15B.
• CodeGen2.5 [22]: Building upon the popular CodeGen2
family of models, CodeGen2.5 with 7B parameters is on
5 par with 15B parameter LCGMs and has undergone additional training on Python. It is developed by Salesforce.
• StarCoder [23]: Trained on 80+ programming languages,
StarCoder supports a novel combination of capabilities and architectural features unavailable in other open
LCGMs. It has 15B parameters.
• CodeGeeX [24]: CodeGeeX is a multilingual code generation model implemented based on the ChatGLM2 architecture. It has 6B parameters and particularly supports
bilingual input in English and Chinese.
• CodeLlama [25]: Developed by Meta, CodeLlama is a
foundational model with various parameter size versions.
We select the 7B version for our study.
• DeepSeek-Coder [26]: This model comprises a series of
code language models trained from scratch on both 87%
code and 13% natural language in English and Chinese. It
supports project-level code completion and infilling. We
choose the 6.7B version here.
• GPT-3.5-Turbo [27]: Developed by OpenAI and empowering ChatGPT, GPT-3.5-Turbo, although not specifically
trained for code generation tasks, can still assist in
programming tasks due to its powerful natural language
understanding and generation capabilities.
E. Parameter Configuration
In our experiments, the maximum time limit Tmax is 6
seconds, the number of sampling k is 100, and the number of
segments seg is 50. Another important parameter when utilizing LCGMs is the temperature (t), which typically ranges from
0 to 1. Lower temperature values result in more deterministic
and concentrated outputs, while higher values lead to more
diverse and exploratory generations. We select two common
temperature values, 0.2 and 0.8, to better observe the impact
of this parameter on the quality of the generated code [28].
IV. RESULTS AND ANALYSIS
A. RQ1: Study on Effectiveness.
Design. In this RQ, we investigate the capability and differences of LCGMs in generating correct code for bilingual
programming questions. Considering the stochastic nature of
the LCGMs’ generation process, we independently execute
the generation process 20 times for each LCGM on each
programming question. If at least one piece of generated code
passes the correctness verification, we consider the LCGM
capable of correctly answering the question. That is, we use the
pass@20 metric to evaluate the correctness of the generated
code. The specific evaluation metrics are discussed in §III-C.
Results. Table II presents the results of our investigation into
the bilingual code generation abilities of LCGMs. The table
is divided into two sections, representing different generation
temperatures (t = 0.2 and t = 0.8) used during code
generation. Each row corresponds to a specific LCGM, and
the columns display various metrics.
Columns CRen and CRzh demonstrate the proportions of
correctly solved programming questions by LCGMs for English and Chinese inputs, respectively. We observe an overall

improvement in the ability to generate correct code as the
temperature increases from 0.2 to 0.8 for most LCGMs (except
CodeGen2.5). We use green and red to highlight the LCGMs
with the highest code correctness. Green indicates that the
model has higher correctness for the questions in English,
while red indicates that the model has higher correctness for
Chinese questions. Obviously, the advantage of generating
correct code is skewed towards English, i.e., when t = 0.2,
only two models gain an advantage in English, but when
t = 0.8, four models gain an advantage in English.
Finding 1: When the temperature is lower, most LCGMs
exhibit higher code generation effectiveness in Chinese
programming questions, while at higher temperatures,
most LCGMs demonstrate higher effectiveness in English
programming questions.
The column CDR demonstrates the disparities in LCGMs’
ability to generate correct code on two language versions of the
same programming question. Particularly, it directly illustrates
the extent to which LCGMs can generate correct code for
one language while producing incorrect code for another. The
results indicate that, across both temperatures, these LCGMs
exhibit inconsistencies in their ability to generate correct code
on over 10% of the programming questions, on average.
Finding 2: LCGMs show inconsistency in generating
correct codes for more than 10% bilingual programming
questions.
In our experiments, GPT-3.5-Turbo and CodeGeeX emerge
as the top performers among the six LCGMs we evaluate,
demonstrating the highest pass rates for code generation in
both English and Chinese individually, as well as achieving the
lowest discrepancy in bilingual effectiveness. It is worth noting
that, when t = 0.2, CodeGeeX outperforms GPT-3.5-Turbo in
both the correctness and consistency of generating codes for
Chinese programming questions. This could be attributed to
the fact that CodeGeeX is developed by a Chinese company
and has undergone more training in Chinese corpora.
B. RQ2:Study on Efficiency.

D. Case Study
Figure 5 illustrates a pair of practical examples for GPT-3.5-
Turbo on bilingual programming tasks. In the first example
in Figure 5(a), GPT-3.5-Turbo generates the correct code for
the Chinese input but fails to do so for the English input.
Specifically, the solution “return total//n” (marked in red) does
not align with the task description of returning the result ”in
a rounded integer.” This further emphasizes the need for an
interpretability-driven comprehensive study regarding which
key entities or information from input problems are captured
by LCGMs for different input languages.
Moreover, we find that even when LCGMs generate functionally correct code for both English and Chinese inputs,
there can still be significant differences in the efficiency
of the generated code. As shown in the second example
in Figure 5(b), the code generated for the Chinese input is less
efficient than that for the English input. The average execution
time complexity of the code generated for the Chinese input
is O(n
2
) due to the presence of nested loops. In contrast,
the code generated for the English input has an average time
complexity of only O(n ∗ log(n)), thanks to the more concise
and efficient library call of “sort()”. This may inspire us that
the subjective enthusiasm of LCGMs for library API calls
may affect the overall efficiency of their generated code. It
is worth noting that to better control variables and ensure that
the Chinese-English differences in the input exist only in the
programming question descriptions, we used the same English
prompt for code generation in both languages.
9 E. Discussions and Suggections
Comprehensive Multilingual Code Generation Quality Assessment: Based on the results from RQ1 and RQ2, our study
has revealed significant disparities in the effectiveness and
efficiency of LCGMs in generating code for bilingual (Chinese
and English) programming. It is reasonable to infer that
such differences are not confined to these two languages but
may represent a broader phenomenon. Emerging research has
increasingly investigated the multilingual understanding and
generation capabilities of Large Language Models [30], and
similar scrutiny must be directed towards LCGMs. Moreover,
effectiveness and efficiency are only two aspects of code
quality, other important attributes such as security, readability, and maintainability also deserve consideration. Therefore,
expanding the scope of quality assessment to include these
additional attributes is a valuable direction for future research.
Developing Better Prompting Methods. According to RQ3,
the impact of different prompting strategies on the quality of
LCGM-generated code is substantial. Prompting techniques
are pivotal in the era of LLMs, and well-crafted prompts can
significantly enhance the quality of generation [31]. Investigating how to construct superior prompts that enable LCGMs
to consistently produce high-quality code across different
languages is of paramount importance.
Adaptive Temperature Tuning. It has been observed that as
the temperature parameter increases, LCGMs exhibit varying
performance across languages, i.e., most LCGMs tend to
prefer generating code of higher quality in English. Identifying
the optimal temperature settings that allow LCGMs to perform
best for each language could be a key factor in improving
multilingual code generation.
In summary, one important message from this study is
that the software engineering community should establish
benchmarks and frameworks for evaluating the multilingual
code generation capabilities of LCGMs, considering different
code quality assessment metrics, input languages, prompting
methods, and more. As an initial step, we have released
our framework [12] and strongly encourage our readers to
contribute more datasets and code quality measurements.
F. Threats to Validity
Limited Dataset: The dataset utilized in this study, despite
careful designing, is limited to 52 bilingual programming questions, which may not sufficiently cover the diverse range of
tasks LCGMs encounter in practical applications. Furthermore,
the dataset only includes English and Chinese, potentially
failing to capture the performance variations of LCGMs across
a wider array of languages. This limitation stems from the
requirement of strong language proficiency to ensure the
quality of multilingual parallel data.
Limited LCGMs: The selected six LCGMs represent the current technology but don’t cover all models or training methods.
However, the selected LCGMs serve as the foundation for
many advanced LCGMs. Our evaluation method is universal
and extendable to a broader range of models.
Evaluation Metrics: The metrics employed in this study
primarily focus on code correctness and efficiency, potentially
neglecting other crucial aspects of code quality, such as readability, maintainability, and adherence to coding standards. The
absence of these factors in the evaluation process may restrict
the comprehensive understanding of the LCGM’ performance.
To mitigate the threats and foster further research, we
make our collected dataset and evaluation framework publicly
available [12]. This initiative aims to empower researchers
to expand the study by incorporating diverse programming
tasks, languages, and quality assessment metrics, as well as to
include a broader range of LCGMs in the comparison.
V. RELATED WORK
A. Large Code Generation Models
LLMs have achieved impressive results in code processing, with models ranging from general-purpose to specialized
architectures. General-purpose LLMs, such as LLaMA [32],
Llama2 [33], LaMDA [34], and PaLM [35], can generate
code thanks to pre-training on text data that includes code.
For example, Llama2 contains 328GB of code from GitHub.
Even smaller models like Phi-1.5 (1.3 billion parameters) can
demonstrate coding proficiency [36].
Language models with additional pre-training on code
have achieved new benchmarks. Codex [8] fine-tuned GPT-3
on 100B code tokens, and PaLM-Coder [35] extended pretraining with 7.8 billion tokens of code. CodeLlama [25]
enhanced Llama2 by pre-training it on 500 billion code
tokens, and CodeFuse-CodeLlama [37], a fine-tuned version
of CodeLlama, surpasses even GPT-4’s performance.
Specialized architecture models use different architectures
to generate code. CodeT5+ [38] uses an encoder-decoder architecture with contrastive objectives, while CodeFusion [39]
introduces diffusion models to code modeling. These models
can outperform other LLMs on code synthesis datasets.
B. Testing and Evaluation for Code Generation Model
Over the years, the software engineering community has
proposed various evaluation tasks to assess code models,
which have been consolidated into benchmarks such as
CodeXGLUE [40] and CodeBLEU [41]. However, with the
introduction of HumanEval [8] and the increasing capability
of code generation models, the focus has shifted towards
functional correctness as a more appropriate metric for evaluation [42], [43], [9]. This has led to the development of metrics
such as pass@k [8] and passn@k [44], which assess the
model’s ability to generate code that passes unit tests. Several
benchmarks have been created to evaluate code synthesis,
including HUMANEVAL and MBPP [9] for Python, as well
as benchmarks targeting other programming languages such as
SQL (Spider[45]), C++, JavaScript, and Go (HUMANEVALX [24]), C++ and Java (CodeContests [44]), and a multilingual
extension of HUMANEVAL and MBPP (MultiPL-E [46]).
In addition to function-level evaluation, CrossCodeEval [47]
and CoderEval [48] have introduced benchmarks for crossfile and project-level code completion. Besides correctness
10 evaluation, some works are dedicated to testing and assessing
the robustness of LCGMs [49], [50], [51], [52], [53].
VI. CONCLUSION
In this paper, we conduct a pioneering empirical study on
the bilingual code generation quality of Large Code Generation Models (LCGMs). While LCGMs have revolutionized
software engineering tasks such as code generation, their
performance on non-English languages, particularly Chinese,
has not been systematically investigated. We collect a dataset
containing 52 bilingual parallel programming tasks and evaluate the code generated by six state-of-the-art LCGMs in
terms of effectiveness and efficiency. Our findings reveal that
there exist quality differences between LCGM-generated code
for English and Chinese programming questions. This work
underscores the urgency for further research and development
to ensure consistent code generation across languages.
